  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Southern Connecticut State?",
  "response": "Selecting the best small classes can depend on your interests and academic goals, but here are some general recommendations for freshmen at Southern Connecticut State University (SCSU) that tend to offer engaging and valuable experiences in a smaller class setting:\n\n1. **First-Year Experience (FYE) Classes**: These are specifically designed for first-year students to help them transition into college life. They often have smaller class sizes and focus on building academic skills, self-discovery, and community engagement.\n\n2. **Honors College Seminars**: If you're part of the Honors College, the seminars offered are typically smaller in size and provide an opportunity for in-depth discussion and study on specialized topics.\n\n3. **Introductory Major-Specific Classes**: Many departments offer introductory courses that may not be large lecture classes. For example, introductory courses in arts, humanities, and sciences sometimes have smaller sections where you can receive more personalized attention.\n\n4. **Writing Intensive Courses**: These classes focus on developing writing skills and usually limit class size to ensure that students receive ample feedback on their writing.\n\n5. **Language Classes**: If you\u2019re interested in learning a new language, these classes tend to be smaller to facilitate interaction and practice.\n\n6. **Seminars and Workshops**: Some departments offer seminars or workshops that are inherently smaller and more discussion-based, allowing for a more personal educational experience.\n\nTo find the best options for your situation, consult with an academic advisor who can provide recommendations based on your interests and program requirements. Additionally, checking the class schedule for courses with low capacity can help identify smaller classes.",
